huntYears.SEASON_DATE_TEXT: Archery: Aug 19 - Sept 15, 2023  Muzzleloader: Sept 27 - Oct 5, 2023  Any Legal Weapon: Oct 21 - Oct 29, 2023

huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION: The majority of land is managed by the BLM and forest Service. There is also a significant amount of private land. This unit does have a Landowner Association. There is private land and some of it is accessible through the DWR’s Walk-in-Access Program (http://wildlife.utah.gov/walkinaccess/).
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS: This is a remote location with some areas with limited access.  Cellular phone coverage is very spotty on this hunt unit.  Digital cell phones may show several bars but cannot always connect due to the distance to the cell towers.  Satellite phones do work in the area.  The biologist suggests hand held radios and even a "Spot Tracker" type of satellite messaging device for safety.  Make sure someone knows where you plan to camp and when you will return.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season.  Be prepared for rain, lightning, snow, wind and heat.  Thunder storms can cause muddy road conditions and rare flash floods in this region.  Most hunters struggle with trying not to get there meat to spoil in the heat.  I would plan on hot weather and plan accordingly.
huntBios.MANAGEMENT_OBJ: 85.7~11200 (entire West Desert unit)~7000 (entire West Desert unit)~25–35~33.5~~~~~~~~For more detailed information on population and objective data please see the Big Game Annual Report Page.
huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
This unit is primarily the Sheeprock and Simpson Mts.. I would not spend precious time/gas (unless you something different) on Desert or Keg Mts. The average buck has been near a 24 inch/4x4. Last year the average slipped down a little but there is still good bucks out there.

Archery: hunters should expect this unit to provide a spot and stalk type archery hunt. Hunter will find bucks to be high in elevation and near stream habitat. Expect dry conditions and monsoon seasons. Weather can change in a heartbeat so be prepared for a down pour. Waterholes may not be a productive hunt method if these conditions occur. Bucks will frequently change up their routine.

Muzzleloader: hunters tend to see many bucks in the canyons the first few days. Expect mid season buck movements to change. Bucks start moving and may not be where you’ve seen them before. Keep looking. I’ve had many reports over the years that bucks are gone the second weekend. They are still there but moved to other canyons or areas.

Any Weapon: hunters should expect changes in weather and possible muddy roads. This unit could experience a wide range of weather events. If it snows I would still expect bucks to remain higher in elevation. Some bucks will transition over to the south side. If the weather is bad expect bucks to be hid in brush and cover.

The Sheeprock and Simpson mountain ranges are remote areas in Utah. There are few service stations. Gas is available in Vernon, Eureka, and Lynndyl. Bring plenty of water, fuel, good tires with extra spares, and plenty of ice. The west or south side is desert and dirt road. Private land holdings limit access to canyons. If you want to hunt those canyons attain permission or go over the top from the other side.

huntMaster.SPECIAL_PROVISIONS: Permit holders may hunt all limited-entry seasons. You must use the appropriate weapon during the appropriate season.
huntMaster.NOTES:
Baiting big game for the purposes of hunting is now illegal in Utah.
Click here for more information.

The use of all trail cameras (including both non-handheld transmitting and non-transmitting devices) in the harvest or to aid in the harvest of big game is prohibited between July 31 and Dec. 31. Click here for more information.
huntMaster.HARVEST_REPORTING: REQUIRED: click here or call 1-800-221-0659 to report your harvest. You must report your harvest, even if you did not take an animal, within 30 days of the season end date that is printed on your permit; failure to do so may result in you not being able to apply for big game species in subsequent years. Submitting teeth or other biological samples from your animal, or having your animal checked by a DWR representative or CWMU operator does NOT fulfill your mandatory harvest reporting requirement.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: The majority of land is managed by the BLM and Forest Service. There is private land as well and some of it is accessible through the DWR’s Walk-in-Access Program (https://wildlife.utah.gov/fishing/walk-in-access.html/).
huntBoundaryInfos.WMA_IN_UNIT: There are no WMA's in this unit.
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
There are many dispersed camping sites within this unit. There are campgrounds located at Vernon Reservoir and Simpson Springs.
Please direct all questions regarding maps and camping regulations to:
Salt Lake BLM Field Office - http://www.blm.gov/office/salt-lake-field-office
USFS- http://www.fs.usda.gov/activity/uwcnf/recreation/camping-cabins
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIM_ACCESS_PTS: Benmore Road, Cherry Creek Road, Pony Express Road, Jericho Junction, Brushwellman Road.
huntBoundaryInfos.SUGGESTED_MAPS: USGS or BLM version 1:100,000 Maps: Lynndyl, Delta, Fish Springs, Rush Valley.
huntBoundaryInfos.COUNTY_ROAD_INFO: most of the roads found on this unit are improved gravel/dirt roads.
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS: There are numerous roads on this unit. Please stay on the roads. Habitat loss effects all wildlife.
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES:
Hunters may notice many areas where juniper trees have been cut down. These activities are to improve wildlife habitat for mule deer and sage-grouse and will have a long-term positive impact.
There are few private ranches that post their property. There are also privately owned lands that allow access or are enrolled through the DWR Walk-in-Access Program. Please be familiar with Utah trespass laws and always be considerate when accessing private lands. Private land is critical to this unit, please stay on the roads, close gates and do not harass livestock.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Juab, Millard and Tooele counties—Boundary begins at SR-36 and the Pony Express road; south on SR-36 to US-6; southwest on US-6 to SR-174 (the IPP road); northwest on SR-174 to the Dugway Valley road; north on this road to the Pony Express road; northeast on this road to SR-36. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Lynndyl, Delta, Fish Springs, Rush Valley. Boundary questions? Call the Springville office, 801-491-5678.
